The push and pull workflow.

Getting an image you built onto a registry is a four-step cycle: tag, login, push, pull. First, you tag your local image with the registry-qualified name, for example, tagging flask-demo as g-h-c-r dot i-o, slash my-org, slash flask-demo, tag zero point one. Second, you authenticate, with docker login g-h-c-r dot i-o. Third, you push that reference. And fourth, elsewhere, someone pulls it and runs it.

Now, what does docker tag actually do? Nothing to the data. It adds another name pointing at the same image: same layers, same digest. That's why you can tag one build as both zero point one and latest, and push both, for the cost of a single upload; they resolve to the same manifest.

And what actually uploads on a push? The daemon walks the image's layers, and for each one, it asks the registry, do you have s-h-a two fifty-six, this digest? That's a head request. If yes, it skips, uploading no bytes. If no, it streams the layer. So a new build that shares ninety percent of its layers with the last one uploads only the changed ten percent. That's the content-addressable deduplication from the previous section, in action, and it's why a push is often far quicker than the image's total size implies.

Here's the key mental correction. A registry name is part of the image reference, not a separate destination. You don't so much push to a place, as rename the image with a registry-qualified name, and then push that name. G-h-c-r dot i-o, slash my-org, slash flask-demo, tag zero point one, is the image's identity on g-h-c-r. Get the tag right, and push and pull are trivial. Get it wrong, with a missing namespace or the wrong host, and you'll get a confusing auth or not-found error. The reference, not the command, is almost always the thing to check.
